OpenPBTA: Explore a PLIER latent variable

CCDL for ALSF

2020

In this notebook, well plot the differences in a single PLIER latent variables values between the 4 medulloblastoma molecular subgroups in our data: Group 3, Group 4, SHH and WNT.

Our objective is to learn more about using the ggplot2 package for a common use case in life science research: visualizing the difference in values between some experimental or clinical group for a single measure.

Often when were working with high-throughout biological data like transcriptomic data, it takes some wrangling to get the data in a format for plotting with ggplot2. So well cover how to do that, too.

First, a note on tidy data

In order to use ggplot2, well need the data in long or tidy format. PLIER outputs what we want to plot in what we call wide format.

Read more about tidy data here.

To quote from Hadley Wickhams R for Data Science:

There are three interrelated rules which make a dataset tidy:

  • Each variable must have its own column.
  • Each observation must have its own row.
  • Each value must have its own cell.

Lets look at a toy example.

set.seed(12345)
toy_df <- data.frame( 
  cbind(c("GENEA", "GENEB", "GENEC"),
        matrix(rnorm(30), ncol = 10))
)
colnames(toy_df) <- c("Gene", paste0("Sample", 1:10))

toy_df is now in wide format.

toy_df

Lets get it into long format.

toy_long_df <- reshape2::melt(toy_df, 
                              id.vars = "Gene", 
                              variable.name = "Sample", 
                              value.name = "Expression")
attributes are not identical across measure variables; they will be dropped
toy_long_df

Lets remove these toy examples from the workspace.

rm(toy_df, toy_long_df)

Directories

# Directory that holds the metadata

PLIER results

# Read in the PLIER results
plier_results <- read_rds(plier_file)
# Filter to LV-pathway relationships with FDR < 0.05
sig_summary_df <- plier_results$summary %>%
  dplyr::filter(FDR < 0.05)
sig_summary_df
# We only want a single instance of each LV index
sig_index <- as.integer(unique(sig_summary_df$`LV index`))
# Get the LV by sample matrix from the PLIER results and subset it to only those
# LVs with an FDR < 0.05 (at least one pathway)
b_matrix <- plier_results$B
sig_b_matrix <- b_matrix[sig_index, ]

# Create a data frame and add a column with LV identifiers
sig_b_wide <- data.frame(sig_b_matrix) %>%
  tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "LV")

Tidy

Lets look at what format this is in currently.

sig_b_wide

We want this in long format. Well use reshape2::melt to do this just like in the toy example above.

sig_b_df <- reshape2::melt(sig_b_wide, 
                           id.vars = "LV", 
                           variable.name = "Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID",
                           value.name = "LV_estimate")
head(sig_b_df)

Now lets add relevant metadata to the data frame so we can use that for plotting.

sig_b_df <- inner_join(x = sig_b_df, 
                       y = histologies_df %>%
                         select(Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID,
                                broad_histology,
                                short_histology,
                                integrated_diagnosis,
                                molecular_subtype,
                                composition),
                       by = "Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID")
Column `Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID` joining factor and character vector, coercing into character vector
head(sig_b_df)

Plotting

Well plot LV57; this is the latent variable that we looked at the loadings for in the previous notebook.

# PLIER names certain latent variables based on their association with input
# gene sets
lv_to_plot <- "57,SVM Macrophages M2"
# For plotting, subset only to the rows corresponding to this latent variable
lv_plot_df <- sig_b_df %>%
  filter(LV == lv_to_plot)

Boxplot and customization

Lets start by making a boxplot.

# Make a boxplot where samples are grouped by molecular subtype
ggplot(lv_plot_df,
       aes(x = molecular_subtype, 
           y = LV_estimate, 
           group = molecular_subtype, 
           colour = molecular_subtype)) +
  geom_boxplot()

It can often be helpful to visualize individual samples.

# Add individual points with geom_jitter()
ggplot(lv_plot_df,
       aes(x = molecular_subtype, 
           y = LV_estimate, 
           group = molecular_subtype, 
           colour = molecular_subtype)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter()

Were able to globally adjust the aesthetics of the jitter points.

# Improve the aesthetics of the points
ggplot(lv_plot_df,
       aes(x = molecular_subtype, 
           y = LV_estimate, 
           group = molecular_subtype, 
           colour = molecular_subtype)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5)

Add a built-in ggplot2 theme.

# Use @jaclyn-taroni's favorite theme :)
ggplot(lv_plot_df,
       aes(x = molecular_subtype, 
           y = LV_estimate, 
           group = molecular_subtype, 
           colour = molecular_subtype)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5) +
  theme_bw()

Use the same color palette we used in the UMAP plot earlier in the module.

# Add colorblindr::scale_color_OkabeIto()
ggplot(lv_plot_df,
       aes(x = molecular_subtype, 
           y = LV_estimate, 
           group = molecular_subtype, 
           colour = molecular_subtype)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5) +
  theme_bw() +
  colorblindr::scale_color_OkabeIto()

Add a title to the plot.

# Use labs() to add a title
ggplot(lv_plot_df,
       aes(x = molecular_subtype, 
           y = LV_estimate, 
           group = molecular_subtype, 
           colour = molecular_subtype)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5) +
  theme_bw() +
  colorblindr::scale_color_OkabeIto() +
  labs(title = lv_to_plot)

Center the title and make it bigger and in bold.

# Use theme() to improve the way the title looks
ggplot(lv_plot_df,
       aes(x = molecular_subtype, 
           y = LV_estimate, 
           group = molecular_subtype, 
           colour = molecular_subtype)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5) +
  theme_bw() +
  colorblindr::scale_color_OkabeIto() +
  labs(title = lv_to_plot) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 15,
                                  face = "bold",
                                  hjust = 0.5))

Use the next chunks to further customize your plot. We might suggest starting with the x- and y-axis labels.

?labs

Adding p-values to a plot

R is great for analyzing genomic data and for publication ready visualizations, but as language for statistical computing, its also great for statistical analysis!

Lets start by

pairwise.wilcox.test(x = lv_plot_df$LV_estimate,
                     g = lv_plot_df$molecular_subtype,
                     p.adjust.method = "bonferroni")

    Pairwise comparisons using Wilcoxon rank sum test 

data:  lv_plot_df$LV_estimate and lv_plot_df$molecular_subtype 

       Group3  Group4  SHH    
Group4 1.00000 -       -      
SHH    0.00071 9e-06   -      
WNT    0.89067 1.00000 0.30052

P value adjustment method: bonferroni

To add the Bonferroni-adjusted p-values for SHH vs.the other subtypes to the plot, we should adjust the y-axis limits to leave room for the labels.

ggplot(lv_plot_df,
       aes(x = molecular_subtype, 
           y = LV_estimate, 
           group = molecular_subtype, 
           colour = molecular_subtype)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5) +
  theme_bw() +
  colorblindr::scale_color_OkabeIto() +
  labs(title = lv_to_plot) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 15,
                                  face = "bold",
                                  hjust = 0.5)) +
  ylim(c(-1.75, 4))

And now were ready to add the adjusted p-values to the plot with ggsignif::geom_signif().

ggplot(lv_plot_df,
       aes(x = molecular_subtype, 
           y = LV_estimate, 
           group = molecular_subtype, 
           colour = molecular_subtype)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5) +
  theme_bw() +
  colorblindr::scale_color_OkabeIto() +
  labs(title = lv_to_plot) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 15,
                                  face = "bold",
                                  hjust = 0.5)) +
  ylim(c(-1.75, 4)) +
  # Note this is highly specific to this plot!
  # This can not be applied to any other plot without significant modification!
  geom_signif(y_position = c(3.5, 3.9, 3.7),
              xmin = c("Group3", "Group4", "SHH"),
              xmax  = c("SHH", "SHH", "WNT"),
              annotations = c("0.00071", "9e-06", "0.30052"),
              tip_length = 0,
              color = "#000000")

Save this final plot to file.

ggsave(filename = boxplot_png, plot = last_plot())
